<li id="cite_note-Donkin2003-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Old_Indic#cite_ref-Donkin2003_7-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFDonkin2003" class="citation book">Donkin, R. A. (2003). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_B4IFMnssyqgC"><i>Between East and West: The Moluccas and the Traffic in Spices Up to the Arrival of Europeans</i></a>. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Philosophical_Society" title="American Philosophical Society">American Philosophical Society</a>. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780871692481" title="Special:BookSources/9780871692481"><bdi>9780871692481</bdi></a>. <q>The modern, regional Indo-Aryan languates developed from Prakrt, an early 'unrefined' (<i>prakrta</i>) form of Sanskrit, around the close of the</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Between+East+and+West%3A+The+Moluccas+and+the+Traffic+in+Spices+Up+to+the+Arrival+of+Europeans&amp;rft.pub=American+Philosophical+Society&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.isbn=9780871692481&amp;rft.aulast=Donkin&amp;rft.aufirst=R.+A.&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Farchive.org%2Fdetails%2Fbub_gb_B4IFMnssyqgC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AIndo-Aryan+languages" class="Z3988"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/></span>
